# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-eks
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-eks/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-eks/cloud-native-computing] Cloud native techniques "enable loosely coupled systems that are resilient, manageable, and observable.
[src:aws-eks/cloud-native-computing] Combined with robust automation, they allow engineers to make high-impact changes frequently and predictably with minimal toil." This independence contributes to the overall resilience of the system, as issues in one area do not necessarily cripple the entire application.
[src:aws-eks/cloud-native-computing] Additionally, such systems are easier to manage, and monitor, given their modular nature, which simplifies tracking performance and identifying issues.
[src:aws-eks/cloud-native-computing] The advantage of using containers is the ability to package all software needed to execute into one executable package.
[src:aws-eks/cloud-native-computing] The container runs in a virtualized environment, which isolates the contained application from its environment.
[src:aws-eks/container-orchestration] In system administration, **orchestration** is the automated configuration, coordination, deployment, and management of computer systems and software.
[src:aws-eks/container-orchestration] Many tools exist for automating server configuration and management.
[src:aws-eks/container-orchestration] Orchestration is often discussed in the context of service-oriented architecture, virtualization, provisioning, converged infrastructure, and dynamic data center topics.
[src:aws-eks/container-orchestration] Orchestration in this sense is about aligning the business request with the applications, data, and infrastructure.
[src:aws-eks/container-orchestration] In the context of cloud computing, the main difference between workflow automation and orchestration is that workflows are processed and completed as processes within a single domain for automation purposes.
[src:aws-eks/container-orchestration] Orchestration, meanwhile, incorporates workflows and provides a directed action towards larger goals and objectives.
[src:aws-eks/container-orchestration] In the context of application programming interfaces (APIs), API orchestration refers to the process of integrating multiple APIs into a unified system to streamline workflows and enhance user experience.
[src:aws-eks/container-orchestration] The approach coordinates the flow of data, the execution sequence, and the dependencies among different APIs to achieve a defined business objective.
[src:aws-eks/container-orchestration] API orchestration is commonly applied in environments that utilize microservices architectures or legacy systems, where the interaction of several APIs is required to complete a task.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:aws-eks/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] In software engineering, a **microservice** architecture is an architectural pattern that organizes an application into a collection of loosely coupled, fine-grained services that communicate through lightweight protocols.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] This pattern allows teams to develop, deploy, and scale services independently, improving modularity, scalability, and adaptability.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] However, it introduces additional complexity, particularly in managing distributed systems and inter-service communication, making the initial implementation more challenging compared to a monolithic architecture.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] There is no single, universally agreed-upon definition of microservices.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] However, they are generally characterized by a focus on modularity, with each service designed around a specific business capability.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] These services are loosely coupled, independently deployable, and often developed and scaled separately, enabling greater flexibility and agility in managing complex systems.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Microservices architecture is closely associated with principles such as domain-driven design, decentralization of data and governance, and the flexibility to use different technologies for individual services to best meet their requirements.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] It is common for microservices architectures to be adopted for cloud-native applications, serverless computing, and applications using lightweight container deployment via OS-level virtualization.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] According to Fowler, because of the large number (when compared to monolithic application implementations) of services, decentralized continuous delivery and DevOps with holistic service monitoring are necessary to effectively develop, maintain, and operate such applications.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] A consequence of (and rationale for) following this approach is that the individual microservices can be individually scaled.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] In the monolithic approach, an application supporting three functions would have to be scaled in its entirety even if only one of these functions had a resource constraint.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] With microservices, only the microservice supporting the function with resource constraints needs to be scaled out, thus providing resource and cost optimization benefits.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Despite its benefits, microservices architecture introduces challenges such as increased operational complexity, network latency, and the need for robust monitoring and fault tolerance mechanisms.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing design in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Each cell operates independently, handling a subset of requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] A cell typically consists of multiple microservices and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] In some implementations, entire sets of microservices are replicated across multiple cells, enabling requests to be rerouted to another operational cell if one experiences a failure.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] This approach is intended to improve system-wide resilience by limiting the impact of localized failures.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Some implementations incorporate circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to mitigate cascading failures among microservices, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in certain large-scale distributed systems where fault isolation and redundancy are design priorities.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Its implementation varies based on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and specific operational goals.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] In 1999, software developer Peter Rodgers had been working on the Dexter research project at Hewlett Packard Labs, whose aim was to make code less brittle and to make large-scale, complex software systems robust to change.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Ultimately this path of research led to the development of resource-oriented computing (ROC), a generalized computation abstraction in which REST is a special subset.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] In 2005, during a presentation at the Web Services Edge conference, Rodgers argued for "REST-services" and stated that "Software components are Micro-Web-Services...
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Micro-Services are composed using Unix-like pipelines (the Web meets Unix = true loose-coupling).
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Services can call services (+multiple language run-times).
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Complex service assemblies are abstracted behind simple URI interfaces.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Also in 2005, Alistair Cockburn wrote about hexagonal architecture which is a software design pattern that is used along with the microservices.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] This pattern makes the design of the microservice possible since it isolates in layers the business logic from the auxiliary services needed in order to deploy and run the microservice completely independent from others.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Determining the appropriate level of (micro)service granularity in a microservices architecture often requires iterative collaboration between architects and developers.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] This process involves evaluating user requirements, service responsibilities, and architectural characteristics, such as non-functional requirements.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Neal Ford highlights the role of integrator and disintegrator factors in this context.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Integrator factors, such as shared transactions or tightly coupled processes, favor combining services, while disintegrator factors, such as fault tolerance or independent scalability, encourage splitting services to meet operational and architectural goals.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Additionally, fitness functions, as proposed by Neal Ford, can be used to validate architectural decisions and service granularity by continuously measuring system qualities or behaviors that are critical to stakeholders, ensuring alignment with overall architectural objectives.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] In microservices architectures, service granularity influences testing, deployment, performance, and reliability.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Very fine-grained microservices are typically easier to test and deploy independently, but they often experience lower performance and reduced overall reliability due to increased interservice communication and more complex service choreography.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Coarse-grained services exhibit contrasting characteristics.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] They generally provide higher robustness and reliability by minimizing communication overhead and coordination complexity, but they are more challenging to test and deploy because modifications affect a broader functional scope.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] The appropriate level of service granularity is determined by business drivers.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Architectural decisions commonly begin with identifying these drivers and then aligning architectural characteristics such as performance, scalability, reliability, or deployment flexibility to support them.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] A bounded context, a fundamental concept in domain-driven design (DDD), defines a specific area within which a domain model is consistent and valid, ensuring clarity and separation of concerns.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] In microservices architecture, a bounded context often maps to a microservice, but this relationship can vary depending on the design approach.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] A one-to-one relationship, where each bounded context is implemented as a single microservice, is typically ideal as it maintains clear boundaries, reduces coupling, and enables independent deployment and scaling.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] The choice of relationship should balance the principles of DDD with the system's business goals, technical constraints, and operational requirements.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] The architecture introduces additional complexity and new problems to deal with, such as latency, message format design, backup/availability/consistency (BAC), load balancing and fault tolerance.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] All of these problems have to be addressed at scale.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] The complexity of a monolithic application does not disappear if it is re-implemented as a set of microservices.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Some of the complexity gets translated into operational complexity.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Other places where the complexity manifests itself are increased network traffic and slower performance.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Also, an application made up of any number of microservices has a larger number of interface points to access its respective ecosystem, which increases the architectural complexity.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Various organizing principles (such as hypermedia as the engine of application state (HATEOAS), interface and data model documentation captured via Swagger, etc.) have been applied to reduce the impact of such additional complexity.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Microservices are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing – a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Ideally, microservices follow a "share-nothing" architecture.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] However, in practice, microservices architectures often encounter situations where code must be shared across services.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Each approach has its advantages and trade-offs, depending on the specific context and requirements.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Richards & Ford in *Fundamentals of software architecture* (2020) propose each microservice should have its own architectural characteristics (a.k.a. non functional requirements), and architects should not define uniform characteristics for the entire distributed system.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] To avoid having to coordinate deployments across different microservices, Sam Newman suggests keeping the interfaces of microservices stable and making backwards-compatible changes as interfaces evolve.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] On the topic of testing, Newman in *Building Microservices* (2015) proposes consumer-driven contract testing as a better alternative to traditional end-to-end testing in the context of microservices.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] He also suggests the use of log aggregation and metrics aggregation as well as distributed tracing tools to ensure the observability of systems composed of microservices.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Computer microservices can be implemented in different programming languages and might use different infrastructures.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Therefore, the most important technology choices are the way microservices communicate with each other (synchronous, asynchronous, UI integration) and the protocols used for the communication (e.g.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] In a traditional system, most technology choices like the programming language impact the whole system.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] Therefore, the approach to choosing technologies is quite different.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] The Eclipse Foundation has published a specification for developing microservices, Eclipse MicroProfile.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] In a service mesh, each service instance is paired with an instance of a reverse proxy server, called a service proxy, sidecar proxy, or sidecar.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] The service instance and sidecar proxy share a container, and the containers are managed by a container orchestration tool such as Kubernetes, Docker Swarm, or DC/OS.
[src:aws-eks/microservices] The service proxies are responsible for communication with other service instances and can support capabilities such as service (instance) discovery, load balancing, authentication and authorization, secure communications, and others.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] On Unix-like operating systems, this feature can be seen as an advanced implementation of the standard chroot mechanism, which changes the apparent root folder for the current running process and its children.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] In addition to isolation mechanisms, the kernel often provides resource-management features to limit the impact of one container's activities on other containers.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] Linux containers are all based on the virtualization, isolation, and resource management mechanisms provided by the Linux kernel, notably Linux namespaces and cgroups.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] Although the word *container* most commonly refers to OS-level virtualization, it is sometimes used to refer to fuller virtual machines operating in varying degrees of concert with the host OS, such as Microsoft's Hyper-V containers.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] For an overview of virtualization since 1960, see Timeline of virtualization technologies.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] On ordinary operating systems for personal computers, a computer program can see (even though it might not be able to access) all the system's resources.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may allow or deny access to such resources based on which program requests them and the user account in the context in which it runs.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may also hide those resources, so that when the computer program enumerates them, they do not appear in the enumeration results.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] Nevertheless, from a programming point of view, the computer program has interacted with those resources and the operating system has managed an act of interaction.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] With operating-system-virtualization, or containerization, it is possible to run programs within containers, to which only parts of these resources are allocated.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] A program expecting to see the whole computer, once run inside a container, can only see the allocated resources and believes them to be all that is available.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] Several containers can be created on each operating system, to each of which a subset of the computer's resources is allocated.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] Each container may contain any number of computer programs.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] These programs may run concurrently or separately, and may even interact with one another.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] Containerization has similarities to application virtualization: In the latter, only one computer program is placed in an isolated container and the isolation applies to file system only.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is commonly used in virtual hosting environments, where it is useful for securely allocating finite hardware resources among a large number of mutually-distrusting users.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] System administrators may also use it for consolidating server hardware by moving services on separate hosts into containers on the one server.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization can also be used to run software created for a certain Linux distribution on another distribution, an example is Distrobox.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] Other typical scenarios include separating several programs to separate containers for improved security, hardware independence, and added resource management features.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] The improved security provided by the use of a chroot mechanism, however, is not perfect.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system-level virtualization implementations capable of live migration can also be used for dynamic load balancing of containers between nodes in a cluster.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] This form of virtualization also does not require hardware support for efficient performance.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is not as flexible as other virtualization approaches since it cannot host a guest operating system different from the host one, or a different guest kernel.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] For example, with Linux, different distributions are fine, but other operating systems such as Windows cannot be hosted.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] Operating systems using variable input systematics are subject to limitations within the virtualized architecture.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] Adaptation methods including cloud-server relay analytics maintain the OS-level virtual environment within these applications.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] Solaris partially overcomes the limitation described above with its branded zones feature, which provides the ability to run an environment within a container that emulates an older Solaris 8 or 9 version in a Solaris 10 host.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] However, in 2010 Linux branded zones were removed from Solaris; in 2014 they were reintroduced in Illumos, which is the open source Solaris fork, supporting 32-bit Linux kernels.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] Some implementations provide file-level copy-on-write (CoW) mechanisms.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] (Most commonly, a standard file system is shared between partitions, and those partitions that change the files automatically create their own copies.) This is easier to back up, more space-efficient and simpler to cache than the block-level copy-on-write schemes common on whole-system virtualizers.
[src:aws-eks/os-level-virtualization] Whole-system virtualizers, however, can work with non-native file systems and create and roll back snapshots of the entire system state.
